{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:23:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:23:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14142"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.38,0.48,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112921"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6822"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94953"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"3998"},{"type":"tags","id":"4699"},{"type":"tags","id":"4997"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12948"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112921"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for advice. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He discloses that he has had sex with multiple male partners in the last year and uses condoms. His last sexual contact was five days ago with a new male partner and they did not use a condom at the time. He states that they plan to be exclusive and engage in unprotected anal intercourse. The patient reveals that his new partner is HIV-positive and on treatment, but has not been attending regular follow-ups. He expresses concern about contracting HIV and asks about prevention strategies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Physical examination reveals no abnormalities. HIV and sexually transmitted infection (STI) screening tests have been performed and are all negative. A full blood examination and renal function tests conducted three months ago were all within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recommend condom use only","Prescribe pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP)","Prescribe post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP)","Advise abstinence from sexual activity","Defer decision until after test results are available"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprescribe pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP)\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient is a man who has sex with men (MSM), and is considering unprotected anal intercourse with a new partner who is known to be HIV positive with unknown viral load. The fact that the partner is not attending regular follow-ups adds uncertainty about their viral suppression status - if the new partner had undetectable viral load on treatment then there would be no additional risk. PrEP is a highly effective HIV prevention strategy for individuals at substantial risk of HIV infection, particularly those with HIV-positive partners, and can be started while waiting for the baseline test results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvising abstinence from sexual activity\u003C/strong\u003E is unrealistic and not in line with current public health approaches to HIV prevention. While abstinence is effective in preventing HIV transmission, it\u0027s not a practical or sustainable recommendation for most individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-exposure prophylaxis (PEP)\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended to be used after a potential exposure to HIV has occurred, with treatment needing to be initiated within 72 hours (3 days) of the exposure. It is not appropriate in this case as the patient\u0027s last sexual contact was 5 days ago which is outside the initiation window for PEP, and therefore the goal here is monitoring for potential disease transmission and ongoing prevention utilising PrEP. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending condom use only\u003C/strong\u003E, while important, is not sufficient as the sole prevention strategy for individuals at high risk, especially with a known HIV-positive partner. Condoms should be used in conjunction with PrEP for optimal protection against HIV and other STIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferring the decision until after test results are available\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially delay the initiation of an effective prevention strategy and put the patient at risk if he engages in unprotected intercourse in the meantime. PrEP is to be started within seven days of the date of the last HIV test, and does not require waiting till the results are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen prescribing PrEP, it\u0027s important to provide comprehensive counselling on adherence, safer sex practices, and the need for regular HIV and STI testing. The most common PrEP regimen is daily oral tenofovir disoproxil fumarate/emtricitabine, which has been shown to reduce the risk of HIV infection by more than 90% when taken as prescribed. The patient should be advised to use condoms in addition to PrEP, especially given the uncertain status of his partner\u0027s viral suppression. Regular follow-up appointments should be scheduled to monitor for side effects, assess adherence, and perform necessary screenings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is recommended for individuals at high risk of HIV acquisition, including men who have sex with men, transgender individuals, and people who inject drugs.","PrEP should be prescribed in conjunction with regular HIV testing, counselling on safer sex practices, and screening for other sexually transmitted infections.","Daily oral PrEP with tenofovir disoproxil fumarate/emtricitabine is highly effective in preventing HIV infection when taken as prescribed."],"references":["Bhatti O, So D, Zahid M, Cornelisse V. Prescribing pre-exposure prophylaxis in general practice. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2021;50:479-82. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/july/prescribing-pre-exposure-prophylaxis-in-general-pr","National PrEP Guidelines Update. Prevent HIV by Prescribing PrEP. In: The Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine (ASHM) [online], Sydney. 2023. Available at: https://prepguidelines.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/ASHM-National-PrEP-Guidelines.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94953"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94953"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T03:36:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T03:39:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6822"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112921"}}},"meta